Final EDITION
Occupy makes inroads
SECTION: A; Pg. 1
LENGTH: 697 two words

CHAPEL HILL ? In the two months on the grounds that Occupy Chapel Hill first set up tents on Franklin Street, the team has commence to make inroads with nearby congregations.
On Sunday, Occupy Chapel Hill protesters visited the United Church of Chapel Hill to talk about the congregation's emotions about the movement, permit protesters to give an explanation for their goals, and to discover factors of unity.
Both intention for a loving neighborhood and eradication of social injustice, stated individuals of both groups.
"The movement is about having a loved community and about how people treat every other," stated Steve Peterson, an Occupy supporter and church member. "And it appears a lot distinctive from how we're residing now."
Prior to the service, Tom Tiemann, an economics professor from Elon University and member of the church, set the stage for th e "99 percent" argument.
He described wealth distribution in the United States, pronouncing the pinnacle 1 percentage of American's make about $500,000 per year, in contrast to the backside 50 percentage who make less than $60,000.
However, Tiemann stated that the real problem was inside the top one-tenth of 1 percent, who make more than $2 million annually.
But Farzin Barazandeh, an Occupy supporter, stated the motion is about more than money.
"We speak a lot about 1 percent, 99 percentage and division of wealth," he said. "But it is something larger than that. It's about social justice."
The United Church has a committee for social justice that works to improve social and economic conditions for the underprivileged.
